 is a hybrid English composed of errors in comprehension-and that such errors enable, rather than hinder, some of the pleasures we take in his language. Investigating how and why it strikes us, by turns, as beautiful, funny, sexy, or smart, she shows how, far from being the fossilized remains of an older idiom, Shakespeare's English is also our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEnglish languagexPsychological aspects. 0aEnglish languageyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 4aaesthetics. 4aeroticism. 4aeuphemism. 4aidioms. 4ainterlanguage. 4alanguage. 4areception. 4atheories of humor. 4atranslation. 4awit. 7aDRAMA / Shakespeare.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360758340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607583.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles